What Makes a Movie Successful?¶

Jesslyn Himawan (Student #: 65088593) & Rashi Selarka (Student #: 90247693)¶

Introduction¶

The English film industry is highly competitive, with hundreds of movies released each year. The number of movies released was significantly higher before the COVID-19 pandemic, with 873 films released in 2018 and 792 films released in 2019 (Statista, 2023). In 2020, when the COVID-19 pandemic hit, the number of movies released dropped by more than half to 334. However, the film industry is slowly recovering from the pandemic, and the numbers have gradually increased over the past two years, with 406 movies in 2021 and 449 movies in 2022 (Statista, 2023). The key metrics for production companies to determine the success of their movies are usually monetary, such as profits. In the 1960s, 20th Century Fox was on the brink of collapse after Cleopatra's lack of success, however, they managed to steer clear of bankruptcy after the success of The Sound of Music in 1965 (Falco, 2015). More recently, Dreamworks Animation had to lay off 350 people to lower costs and increase profit margins, partly due to the poor performance of Rise of the Guardians released in 2012 (Fritz, 2013).

Thus, understanding the factors contributing to a movie's success is crucial for production companies and producers to make informed decisions and maximize profitability. With this project, we aim to gain insights into factors that may help determine the success of a movie by performing multilinear regression analysis to develop predictive models.

We were able to find following data set on Kaggle: Movie Dataset: Budgets, Genres, Insights (Singh, 2023), that contains a comprehensive set of information and industry analytics for over 3000 English movies, such as the budget, revenue, viewer ratings, genre(s), etc. Since we aim to understand factors that contribute to a movie's success from the firms' perspective, we will use profit (the difference between the revenue and budget) and profit margin (the profit relative to the revenue in %) as our measures of success. We wanted to investigate both variables because the relative nature of profit margin could make it a better indicator of success over time - it accounts for inflation over the years, unlike the raw profit values. We intend to fit 2 models - one model that predicts profit, and one that predicts the profit margin - and determine which one may be a better measure of success. Of the many available, we decided to use the following explanatory variables for both models - budget, genre, runtime and average viewer ratings (vote_average). The reason we chose budget is that a higher budget on most projects indicates greater quality of production, more qualified professionals being hired, and more marketing, all of which are expected to bring in relatively larger revenue, thus inflating profitability (Lang, 2009). The genres that a movie is classified into are also believed to have a correlation with the box office revenue they generate, with adventure and action films bringing in the most money (Statista, 2023). Multimedia research has also demonstrated that runtime (length of movie) as well as the user reviews for a movie can affect its box office performance (E Souza, Nishijima, & Pires, 2023) (Chintagunta, Gopinath, & Venkataraman, 2010), and therefore we thought these would be good predictors to consider for our models.

Methodology¶

We firstly loaded the packages, data, and then cleaned it - to look at it in more detail, the Data Cleaning file can be found here: Data Cleaning.

We will be using the variables revenue and budget for each movie to calculate the values of profit and profitmargin using the following formulae:

\begin{equation*} \text{Profit} = \text{Revenue} - \text{Budget} \end{equation*}\begin{equation*} \text{Profit Margin} = \frac{\text{Profit}}{\text{Revenue}} \times 100 \end{equation*}

Something we recognize, is that profit, profit margin, and budget as variables have incredibly large values compared to the rest of the dataset, and we thought it would be interesting to make them non-linear features of our linear model by taking their log instead - creating the variables logbudget, logprofit and logprofitmargin.

#Creating values for log(budget), log(profit), and log(profitmargin)

df['logbudget'] = np.log(df["budget"]) # Creating log(budget)
df['logprofit'] = np.log(df["profit"]) # Creating log(profit)
df['logprofitmargin'] = np.log(df["profitmargin"]) # Creating log(profitmargin)

# Replacing negative infinity values for logprofit and logprofitmargin with 0

df["logprofit"].replace(-np.inf, 0, inplace=True)
df["logprofitmargin"].replace(-np.inf, 0, inplace=True)

For genre, the data simply provides a string of all the genres a movie belongs to - in order to make it usable in our models, we will be generating 7 dummy variables, each of which will check to see if the movie is classified in that genre or not. The 7 genres we are splitting into are Drama, Action, Comedy, Fantasy, Horror, Animation, and Documentary. There are multiple subgenres that we are classifying into the above genres as well (e.g. Romance and Mystery are both under Drama).

When comparing log(Profit) against log(Budget) using Fig 5.1, we can see that log budget mostly positively correlates with log profits, but there are a few points of higher budget that correlate with lower profit. These points represent blockbuster films that had large budgets but massively underperformed. Having a higher budget also means higher financial risk, as insufficient revenues would result in bigger losses. All of this probably means that the relationship between log(Budget) and log(Profit) may not be strictly linear.

When comparing log(Profit Margin) against log(Budget) using Fig 5.2, it's a bit hard to read what the relationship might be. While there are lot of data points concentrated around higher log budgets and higher log profit margins, there are quite a few points that are extremely low as well. As previously mentioned, higher budgets would allow for more resources to be allocated to things that could result in a more successful movie, and if the expenses are managed effectively, it can lead to a positive profit margin. However, it is not a guarantee. Other factors, such as competition, genre trends, and changing costs for making movies also play crucial roles in determining the profitability.

Correlation Heat Map & Multilinear Regression Analysis¶

W will use explanatory variables, log(Budget), Runtime, Average Viewer Rating, and Genre of the movies, to create two models:

  1. a model that predicts the log(profit) for a movie.
$$\text{log(Profit)} = \beta0 + \beta1 * \text{log(budget)} + \beta2 * \text{runtime} + \beta3 * \text{viewer rating} + \beta4 * \text{is drama} +\beta5 * \text{is action} + \beta6 * \text{is comedy} + \beta7 * \text{is fantasy} + \beta8 * \text{is horror} + \beta9 * \text{is animation} + \beta10 * \text{is documentary}+\epsilon$$
  1. a model that predicts the log(profit margin) for a movie.
$$\text{log(Profit Margin)} = \beta0 + \beta1 * \text{log(budget)} + \beta2 * \text{runtime} + \beta3 * \text{viewer rating} + \beta4 * \text{is drama} +\beta5 * \text{is action} + \beta6 * \text{is comedy} + \beta7 * \text{is fantasy} + \beta8 * \text{is horror} + \beta9 * \text{is animation} + \beta10 * \text{is documentary}+\epsilon$$

These models above do not include any interactions between the explanatory variables - therefore, we will first check the correlation between our variables to see if there is any multicollinearity and thus any interactions we may need to consider.

In [15]:
# Dropping any null values

df.dropna(inplace=True)
In [16]:
# Creating a correlation heat map for the predictors to check for any multicollinearity

xvars = ["logbudget", "runtime", "vote_average", "isdrama", "isaction", "iscomedy", "isfantasy", "ishorror", "isanimation", "isdoc"]

dfcorr = df[xvars]
corr = dfcorr.corr(method='pearson')
mask = np.zeros_like(corr, dtype=bool)
mask[np.triu_indices_from(mask)] = True

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6, 5))

cmap = sns.diverging_palette(220, 10, as_cmap=True, sep=100)

sns.heatmap(corr, mask=mask, cmap=cmap, vmin=-1, vmax=1, center=0, linewidths=.5)
fig.suptitle('Fig 8 - Correlation Matrix of Predictors', fontsize=15)
fig.tight_layout()

Based on Fig 8, there is no strong multicollinearity between any variables, and hence there are no interactions to be considered.

R-squared values¶

We see that the R-squared value for our log(Profit) model is not the greatest (0.349) in general, since R-squared values under 0.4 are considered indicative of poor explanatory power. However, these standard vary from field to field - for models in natural sciences like Chemistry, R-squared standards are higher. But in economic models, particularly those with many variables such as ours, an R-squared value near 0.3 can also be an impressive one to start with (Valchanov, 2023), and this value can then be further strengthened with the additional parameters removed from or constraints set for the model.

As for our log(Profit Margin) model, the R-squared value isn't as well performing as the log(Profit) model (0.080). R-squared values this close to 0 demonstrate that the predictor variables very weakly explain the predicting variable, and we believe this is likely due to the predictors and log(Profit Margin) having a non-linear relationship. Going back to fig. 4.1 - 4.8, 5.2, 6.2, and 7.2, there appears to be an inverted exponential or logistic curve that describes the relationship between log(Profit Margin) and the predictor variables, indicating that perhaps a logistic regression would result in a better fit for this data. The variables might still be relevant, because the R-squared value does not indicate whether certain variables should be kept or removed, but it certainly shows us that the logbudget, runtime, genre, and viewer ratings in a linear model are not doing the best job of predicting log(Profit Margin). Therefore, with reference to the R-squared statistic, the log(Profit) model is the better fitting model of the two.

# RMSE for log(Profit Margin) model

y = df["logprofitmargin"].values

RMSE for log(Profit Margin): 0.6675

Moving onto the RMSE, there appears to be a contrasting result. The RMSE of the log(Profit Margin) model (0.6675) is lower than that of the log(profit) model (1.3333), and lower RMSEs are considered better for models since they indicate a lower standard deviation for residuals (i.e. the distance between predicted and true values). So the RMSE provides an estimation of how well the model is able to predict the target value, or its accuracy. According to the RMSE statistics found above and after considering the range of values for log(Profit) and log(Profit Margin), the log(Profit Margin) model seems to be more accurate than the log(Profit) model.

AIC¶

Lastly, the AIC. The AIC is also a measure of goodness of fit, with the lower AIC indicating a better fitting model. As seen in the tables above, the AIC for the log(Profit Margin) model (4799) is lower than that for the log(Profit) model (8057), so the log(Profit Margin) model would be considered the better fit model according to the AIC. However, there are limitations to using these statistics - which we will discuss in our next section.

Discussion¶

Generally, there is a higher amount of movies with higher profits in recent years compared to the 1900s for most of the genres due to changing production costs and currency value. A concern we had with using Profit as an indicator of success is inflation and the diminishing value of money over time. Profit Margin takes into account the ratio of profit to revenue instead of absolute profit values, providing a measure of success that accounts for the scale of the movie's production and allows for a more meaningful comparison across different time periods. Therefore, we expected the model evaluation statistics to largely favour the log(Profit Margin) model. The statistic for accuracy, RMSE, corroborates that expectation, but the statistics for predictive power, the R-squared value and the AIC are conflicting - one supports the log(Profit) model and the other the log(Profit Margin) model.

The reason it is slightly more complicated as well are that while the R-squared value for our log(Profit) model may or may not indicate a decent fit model, we can still look at our visualizations and tell that perhaps these variables don't share a linear relationship with each other. So in the future, we can look to fitting a non-linear model for profit (perhaps logistic or a regression tree) and to also implement a model selection algorithm that can avoid instances of us filling our model with inappropriate parameters.

Something to note about the AIC as well is that it essentially generates scores by comparing many probably models and choosing the best one, but it doesn't say anything about the absolute quality of any of the models. i.e. if all our models are poor, it simply chose the best of a bad bunch. Therefore, an additional step after picking a model the AIC favours, is that we can consider running a hypothesis test to figure out the relationship between the explanatory variables and the outcome of interest.

It is also important to note that some of the genres used as explanatory variables, such as Fantasy, Horror, Animation and Documentary, contains significantly less movies compared to other genres in our dataset, as seen in Fig 1. In the future, we can look into using a larger dataset to potentially improve our model. In addition, the genre Drama, consists of movies in the Drama, Thriller, Mystery, Adventure, Romance, Western, and Music subgenres. In the future, breaking down the Drama category may also help improve our models.

Conclusion¶

The fact that we chose to do linear regression (albeit with a few non-linear features) did not result in failing models, but certainly weaker models. The model sumarries found near the end that tell us this set of predictors and target variable likely share a non-linear relationship, so fitting a logistic regression or a regression tree in the future would be an interesting investigation. The explanatory variables we chose for the log(Profit) and log(Profit Margin) models also may not necessarily have been the optimal ones, and future projects in this vein should intend to implement a model selection algorithm to ensure the best parameters are present.

Following the discussion above, it is, in fact, difficult to determine if one model entirely trumps the other, since one appears to be more accurate but the other appears to have more predicting power. Hence, something that could be considered is both models working in tandem towards a "success function". Similar to the production functions we've worked with before, one can consider making a success function using Profit and Profit Margin (or in our models' case, log(Profit) and log(Profit Margin)) in order to generate an overall success score for a film. Something they can look towards doing is based on the predictability and accuracy of each of the models, determining the weight / coefficient ($\alpha$) associated with each of their terms in a success function of type:

$$ \text{Success} = \alpha_1 * \text{Profit} \ \ + \ \ \alpha_2 * \text{Profit Margin}$$
